# polymorphism :- 
# In Python, polymorphism is a core concept of Object-Oriented 
# Programming (OOP) that allows different objects to be treated as 
# instances of the same general class through the same interface.

# The word itself comes from Greek: poly (many) and morph (forms).
#  In short, it’s the ability of a single function, method, or symbol to behave 
# differently depending on the "form" (data type) it is acting upon.
# ------
# Polymorphism in Python is the ability of an object,
# function, or operator to take on multiple forms or behave differently 
# depending on the specific data type or class it is operating on.

#  types of polymorphism in python include:

# method overloading
#  :- same name of the method (function ) but different parameters.

# method overriding 


# method overloading (is  not using python) :-
# Python does not support method overloading in the traditional sense (as found in statically typed languages like Java or C++)
# primarily due to its dynamic typing and the way it manages namespaces. 


